<br>
What is the purpose of manslaughter laws?  What is the purpose of the prison sentences that these laws carry as punishment if you break them?<br>
<br>
They order and regulate society, and the punishments are designed to (the debate goes on) rehabilitate and/or remove from society a person who has proven themselves to be, one way or another, detrimental to it.<br>
<br>
You're acting as if she is just like the woman who drowned her kids, or the one who left her child in the car while shopping.  Maybe if you could somehow prove gross neglect on her part, you could stick a charge on her, but apart from one neighbor's unsubstantiated accusation, we have nothing!  Yet you all assume that there is *criminal neglect* going on here.<br>
<br>
Flevius put it well.  Could she have avoided the child's death?  Yes.  Was she <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>criminally negligent</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->?  Barring evidence showing conclusively that she habitually encouraged or allowed her children to play in her parked car, the answer is NO.<br>
<br>
How many of you broke a limb when you were kids?  Should your parents be jailed for pain &amp; suffering? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=loeganwolfheart>Loegan Wolfheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Please do things my way, thx.</span><br>  Posts: 3901<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/5/03 10:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1795.topic&index=90>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://loegan.homestead.com/files/rn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ..</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>If you think other people should be responsible for her child you’re a bigger idiot then I first thought.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Actually, I think that was one of the most true things Hillary Clinton ever said - &quot;It takes a village to raise a child&quot;.<br>
<br>
When I was growing up, if I was seen doing something wrong by one of my neighbors, I would get spoken to at the least. If that wasn't enough they would have spoken to my grandparents (who raised me after my mother died). At the same time, if I needed help building a soap box racer, fixing my bike or advice on fishing... whatever. I knew I could ask my neighbors. <br>
<br>
It was not unusual to see the neighbors playing with the kids, even the ones who had none of their own. There was a feeling of belonging. Even the kids without dad's had male influences in their lives and somebody to look up to.<br>
<br>
I think alot of the problems today are a result of everybody &quot;minding their own business&quot;. Neighbors should be more aware of each other and responsible for each other. When we as a nation had that type of mentality, I think it was far more pro than con. I imagine there are places where that type of attitude still exists, but on the whole we are much more disconnected now... at least in that respect. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=seieli>Seieli</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/5/03 10:52 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm12.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1795.topic&index=91>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Hmm</span><hr size=1> Actually, criminal negligence isn't based on repetition, it's based on how a reasonable person would behave.  It's up to the judge or jury to decide whether or not a reasonable person typically leaves a child that young unattended for that length of time, while <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>providing an environment</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> where harm or death could occur.  Like unlocked doors and unlocked cars, and the child being found previously alone in the car before.<br>
<br>
